iographical Note to Nabokov’s Dozen (1958)


“The Aurelian,” “Cloud, Castle, Lake,” and “Spring in Fialta” were originally written in Russian. They were first published (as “Pilgram,” “Oblako, ozero, bashnya,” and “Vesna v Fial’te”) in the Russian émigré review Sovremennyya Zapiski (Paris, 1931, 1937, 1938) under my pen name V. Sirin and were incorporated in my collections of short stories (Soglyadatay, Russkiya Zapiski publisher, Paris, 1938, and Vesna v Fial’te 